I think you are trying to implement a factory pattern. In that case, you can make the `Employee` class `abstract`. Because there will be no `Employee` who is just an `Employee`. It has to be either a `Manager` or a `Worker`. As you are using polymorphism, you don&#39;t need to keep the `status` in the `Employee` class. You can find what type of employee it is by its type. So, your class hierarchy becomes

**Employee.java**
```Java
public abstract class Employee {

    private int employeeID;
    private double salary;

    //Constructor
    public Employee(int ID, double esalary) {
        employeeID = ID;
        salary = esalary;
    }

    //Getter ID
    public int getID() {
        return employeeID;
    }

    //Setter ID
    public void setID(int ID) {
        employeeID = ID;
    }

    //Getter Salary
    public double getSalary() {
        return salary;
    }

    //Setter Salary
    public void setSalary(double esalary) {
        salary = esalary;
    }
}
```
**ManagerEmployee.java**
