As a starting point, i would suggest you to read the official Stompjs guide page, and avoid SockJs as it states here, because it generates more problems than it solves:

&gt; In reality, there is very little chance that you need SockJS. Unless you know, for sure, you do not need SockJS.

 [Stomp-js docs][1]

So, in your spring config file, you can remove the &quot;.withSockJS();&quot; part. The rest of the config looks fine.

You can create the websocket client on front end, directly from Stompjs, like that:

    import { Client } from &#39;@stomp/stompjs&#39;;

    const newClient = new Client({
      // Remember Stomp goes over WS protocol, not on HTTP like SockJs
      brokerURL: &quot;ws://localhost:8080/ws&quot;, 

      // Optional configurations
      connectHeaders: {
        login: &quot;yyy&quot;,
        passcode: &quot;xxx&quot;
      },
      debug: function (str) {
        console.log(str);
      },
      reconnectDelay: 5000,
      heartbeatIncoming: 4000,
      heartbeatOutgoing: 4000,

      // Custom onConnect function (whatever you like, useState, etc.)
      onConnect: () =&gt; setConnected(true),

      onStompError: (frame) =&gt; {
        console.log(&#39;Broker reported error: &#39; + frame.headers[&#39;message&#39;]);
        console.log(&#39;Additional details: &#39; + frame.body);
      },
      onWebSocketError: (it) =&gt; {
        console.log(JSON.stringify(it));
      }
    });
    
    newClient.activate();

Other functions (subscribe, unsubscribe, publish, deactivate) are pretty straight forward.

(I strongly suggest you to use a React Context for the websocket operations, and be really aware where/when do you connect/disconnect,  if you want to avoid multiple socket connections per user nightmare)

The connectivity problem should still keep going with this changes, in my opinion, you should first test, that socket is connecting correctly without doing anything else.

I would remove the &quot;client.send&quot; and &quot;client.subscribe&quot; that you have in your onConnect function, and I would see if simple connection is working.

Check on your front-end dev-tools if, on network section, requests to /ws are successful or not. If not, provide also front-end logs or network requests statuses.

